Boil a large #pot of salted @water{to taste} for the @dried linguine{180%grams}.

Halve and peel the @onion{1}. Thinly slice half (double for 4p).

Roughly chop the @mushrooms{150%grams}.

Halve and deseed the @bell pepper{1}. Chop into 1cm chunks.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

When the water is boiling, add the linguine and bring back to the boil.

Cook until softened, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander and pop back in the pot, off the heat.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and stir through to prevent sticking.

Meanwhile, place a #pan over medium heat (without oil).

Once hot, dry-fry the @pine nuts{10%grams} until lightly toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}. Remove from the pan and set aside.

Return the pan to medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once the oil is hot, add the @Irish bacon lardons{100%grams}.

Fry until golden, stirring occasionally, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Cook lardons thoroughly.

Lower the heat to medium then add the onion, mushrooms and pepper to the pan.

Cook, stirring occasionally, until softened and starting to brown, ~{4-5%minutes}.

With 1 min of cooking time left, add the garlic and cook until fragrant, stirring frequently.

Add @water{50%ml}, @vegetable stock{1%sachet} and @Italian herbs{1/2%sachet} to the pan.

Bring to the boil then lower the heat.

Simmer until slightly reduced, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir the @creme fraiche{110%grams} through the sauce.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if you feel the sauce is too dry.

Add the drained linguine to the sauce and toss everything together.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and plenty of @pepper{to taste}.

Serve in #bowls and finish with a sprinkling of @grated Italian style hard cheese{2%sachet} and a scattering of pine nuts.